Under the Howey test, a security is a "a contract, transaction or scheme whereby a person invests his money in a common enterprise and is led to expect profits solely from the efforts of the promoter or a third party.”
Tao is more like  tokens used to access a service.  Those tokens may or may not have value, but the value is tied to the usefulness of the service.
And it is definitely not a situation where one is expected to profit solely from the efforts of a promoter or third party.
This is a simplification, however.
what is meant by "a common enterprise"?

You would really have to look at bunches of case law.  The classic example is I've got a business selling widgets.  You give me money and I promise to give you a share of the profits.  I and my partners and employees are doing all the work - this work is a common enterprise.
Because you are not participating in the work, you are expecting profits solely from the efforts of a third party. Thus it is a security
We are 100% participating in this work 😭😭😭😭😭
In bittensor's case, they are not selling tokens to anyone, and you have to materially participate in work to earn them.
Tao is a lot more analogous to BTC.  And while the SEC has said nothing official, most commentators and officials inside the SEC have repeatedly said that BTC is not a security.

Understandable.  There was a tax case in Tennessee (ferderal court) that ruled that mined crypto is not taxed on mining.  It is considered a created property, like creating a piece of art or baking a pie for sale.  Thus, you only recognize taxable income when you sell the property.
Now this is not yet binding precedent on the whole country, but it has received favorable commentary from those who are into that stuff.

Tao is not yet a security token classified by the SEC. At least according to our legal team 🙂 

To get into more detail, this project did not have an ICO or a pre-mine, we followed a bitcoin-style fair launch where every tao is mined. This means that it's not quite a "security" because it doesn't yet meet that definition. It's an asset generated by compute. We must reach decentralization before we can list on a CEX and avoid all SEC implications. To do that, we have to pass something called the Howey test (basically determines that an investment contract exists if there is an "investment of money in a common enterprise with a reasonable expectation of profits to be derived from the efforts of others."). Once Bittensor is decentralized enough similarly to other decentralized tokens, it will pass this test. Until then, we are taking the parachain auctions route so that we can reach decentralization without risking placing ourselves in SEC jeopardy by going for a full CEX listing.

The other tidbit here, is that we are custodians and creators of the project. We cannot actually list it in a CEX before it's decentralized enough or else we risk getting under the SECs radar (since people who have mined from the beginning like us stand to benefit from this, it's a conflict of interest). If someone else completely unrelated to us lists it, it's a different story. We've been trying to follow the rule of law here so that the project can gain credibility and so we can have no hiccups when listed *cough* ripple *cough*

Is there really a difference between OTC sales and selling tokens to private groups?
ok_LG
Yeah. One is a private sale.  the other is a private offering.  It may sound like a distinction without a difference, but the code treats them differently.
Its like a spectrum. On one side you have a private sale to someone you know.  Definately not an offering of a security, even if the underlying thing is a security.
On the other end, you put up a website and take out a superbowl ad and sell to anyone who wants to buy.  Definitely an offering, and a public offering at that.
Hedgefunds, VC's, investment banks, all these folks are exempt from "investor protection" as they are deemed sophisticated investors.
Accredited investors are exempt from most, but not all, investor protections.
Joe Schmoe off the street has to suffer under all of the investor protections. Therefore, virtually no investments that are not through stock brokers or similar outfits are made available to him.
Now if Joe happens to be buddies with the owner of a new company, that company owner can usually sell to his friend in an OTC transaction without much risk.
The further Joe gets away from that close interaction, the more risk there is to the company.
Of course, all of this only matters if Tao is a security, and I don't think it is.  Especially the way the team is managing things.
